      en: 'The first farming communities settled the river valleys and coastal plains of what would become Normandy, and the same megalith-building world extended to the Channel Islands. They raised dolmens, menhirs, and allées couvertes — stone monuments that marked burial sites, sacred gathering places, and territorial claims over the landscape for more than three thousand years.',
